desc: Horizontally scalable pub-sub messing. Use the 0.8.x or later Kafka, as prior versions are not compatible and had design flaws. Queue holds a fixed window of the most recent messages (usually set large enough for at least a day's worth of messages), with clients responsible for tracking their own consumption.
name: Apache Kafka

desc: Robust generalized object/blob store. Latencies higher than disk access, but highly scalable throughput and very economical storage costs.

desc:
Handy way to bypass HTTP overhead. Particularly handy for push notifications... if you can handle a large number of open sockets. There are a lot of implementations out there, many with security issues, so be sure to use an up to date solution.

Note that SPDY & HTTP/2 significantly reduce the scenarios where WebSockets would be helpful.
name: WebSocket

desc: Content-Security-Policy, one of many HTTP headers designed to fight the never ending XSS war.
name: CSP: Content Security Policy

desc: Worth keeping an eye on, but so far efforts to use it have not gone well.
name: AWS ECS

desc: AWS equivalent to Kafka: provides high throughput, reliable, partially ordered, horizontally scalable pub-sub style messaging. Like with Kafka, clients need to keep track of where they are in the queue. Is generally more limited than Kafka, but nicely integrated with other AWS services and of course requires no operational support.
name: AWS Kinesis

desc: Custom fixed dictionary for data compression. Generally increases compression ratios while reducing server load for services where data is static or has highly consistent redundant structures (like XML documents). Supported by a majority of browsers (but not all). Requires *significant* precompute time that make it prohibitive for more dynamic data sources.
name: SDCH HTTP compression
